ades to investigate how taxes affect a range of household behavior, including labor-force participation, saving behavior, choice of health insurance plan, choice of child care arrangements, portfolio choice, and tax evasion. They also present new analytical results on the effects of different types of tax policy. All of this research relies on household-level data—drawn either from public-use tax return files or from large household-level surveys—to explore various aspects of the relationship between taxes and household behavior. As debates about the effects of proposed tax reforms continue in the 1990s, this volume will be of interest to policy makers and scholars in the field of public finance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aalternative tax rules, reform, taxation, policy, rates, revenue collections, household decisions, evasion, portfolio choice, child care, health insurance, saving, labor force participation, employment, unemployment, finance, nonfiction, economics, government, passive losses, income, consumption, audit, federal, state, deductions.1 aAlm, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEissa, Nada, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErard, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeenberg, Daniel R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeinstein, Jonathan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldstein, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldstein, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGentry, William M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruber, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo